mergence of public opinion as a political force. This book reconstructs the lives of the political pamphleteers as well as the political landscape of late fourteenth-century England, giving particular emphasis to the large group of bureaucrats living in London to which Geoffrey Chaucer belonged. Dr Clementine Oliver is Associate Professor of History at California State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in politicsxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 0aCommunication in politicszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPamphleteersxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 0aPamphleteerszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPamphletsxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 0aPamphletszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846158568?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158568/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles